Vegeta1

Target IP: 192.168.170.73

Scanning



Looks like there are only two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP. I will start my enumeration with the HTTP application.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed when I browse to this port from my browser. The source-code of the HTML does not provide anything useful either. Time for a directory search against this port.


Doing a basic directory search highlight important information, such as the admin and robots.txt.


The robots.txt mentions a hidden directory with the name /find_me.


Browsing to /find_me points to a file called find_me.html and viewing the source-code of this page contains a base64 string at the end.



After decoding the base64 string, I converted that into a QR code. Using a QR code decoder, I obtained the password topshellv. But what is this password for? This password did not work for vegeta:topshellv The admin directory is interesting as it contains a file. Fuzzing this file for LFI and parameter names did not work either. The two images vegeta.jpg and vegeta1.jpg did not have any hidden data inside using steganography either.


Running a gobuster scan with rockyou.txt highlights another hidden directory with the name bulma.


And there is one wav file with the name hahahaha.wav. I downloaded this on my machine. The audio is in morse-code because of the beeps.


Using an online morse-code decoder, I obtained the message which is USER:TRUNKS PASSWORD:US3R<KN>S IN DOLLARS SYMBOL). So we now have trunks:u$3r.

Exploitation


Trying the credentials above worked with SSH. I now have foothold on the machine.

Privilege Escalation


The /etc/passwd file is writeable as trunks. Meaning, we can create a new user with root privileges!


I used echo '' >> /etc/passwd to append a new line. Then I generated a new password using openssl passwd super, and then appended it inside the /etc/passwd file using the command
echo 'super:PbvBTKSv/sfc2:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash' >> /etc/passwd. Now it's just switching to the new user using su super with the password super.


Aaaaaaand I am root using the new user.

Flags


The local.txt flag once I gained foothold on the machine as trunks.


The proof.txt flag once I created a new root user and appended it inside the /etc/passwd file.
